{{Infobox person | name =Hamilton Douglas Halyburton | image =Halyburton Memorial Sandy Hook.jpg | image_size = | caption =Halyburton Memorial at [[Sandy Hook, New Jersey]] | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1763|10|10}} | birth_place = | death_date = {{Death date and age|1783|12|31|1763|10|10}} | death_place =[[Sandy Hook, New Jersey]] | death_cause = | resting_place =[[Sandy Hook, New Jersey]] | resting_place_coordinates = | residence = | nationality = | other_names = | known_for = | education = | employer = | occupation = | title = | salary = | networth = | height = | weight = | term = | predecessor = | successor = | party = | boards = | religion = | spouse = | partner = | children = | parents =[[Sholto Douglas, 15th Earl of Morton]] | relatives = | signature = | website = | footnotes = }}
'''Hamilton Douglas Halyburton''' (10 October 1763 – 31 December 1783) was a British Lieutenant who died at [[Sandy Hook, New Jersey]].
==Biography== He was born on 10 October 1763 to [[Sholto Douglas, 15th Earl of Morton]].<ref name=admiralty/><ref name=wein>{{cite book |author=[[Stanley Weintraub]] |coauthors= |title=General Washington's Christmas Farewell |year=2003 |publisher= |quote=The next morning, the bodies of all but one of them, including Lieutenant Hamilton Douglas Haliburton, brother of the Earl of Morton, washed up on a beach ... | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dF_2xMjpXRoC&pg=PA89 |isbn=0743246543 }}</ref> He died on 31 December 1783 when he was in command of the [[barge]] of the {{HMS|Assistance|1781|6}}. He was using it to chase deserters off of Sandy Hook. He and his crew were caught in a [[winter storm]] and they all died, all but one of the bodies washed ashore the next day.<ref name=wein/> They were described as "12 gentlemen and one common sailor".
==Halyburton Memorial== Katherine Hamilton, the Countess Dowager of Morton erected a monument, but it was destroyed by the French.<ref>{{cite book |last= |first= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=The Geographical and Historical Dictionary of America and the West Indies |year=1814 |publisher= |quote=During the American war, the Countess Dowager of Morton erected, on the w. side of Sandy Hook, a fine monument of marble to the memory of her son, Lieutenant Halliburton, of the royal navy, who, together with a boat's crew, perished there in a snow storm. A few years ago this work of parental affection was beat down and destroyed, by the crew of a French armed ship, in a manner that reflects no honour upon their professional or manly feelings. | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9mQFAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA383&lpg=PA383&dq=Haliburton+%22Sandy+Hook%22&source=bl&ots=QfQM53eygH&sig=UfXmIig1RjRXBSluapVyh95NVWE&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=1&ct=result |isbn= }}</ref> The grave was rediscovered in 1908 during expansion of a road.<ref name=admiralty>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Admiralty Acknowledges Kindness in Burying Bodies of Officers Frozen in 1783. |url=http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:NYT_Halyburton.gif |quote=Fourteen from the Assistance Searching for Deserters Died. French Vandals Destroyed Their Monument. The Admiralty has issued a notice recalling a lamentable and unfortunate occurrence which took place in December, 1783, just after the declaration of peace with the United States of America. The circumstance is thus describe in Brenton's "Naval History," (Vol. I., Page 261, 1837,) although the date is incorrectly given, probably a misprint. ... son of Sholto Charles, Earl of Morton ...|work=[[New York Times]] |date=September 6, 1908 |accessdate=2009-01-23 }}</ref>
In 1937, a new Halyburton Memorial was constructed.<ref>{{cite web|title=Revolutionary War Sites in Sandy Hook, New Jersey |url=http://www.revolutionarywarnewjersey.com/new_jersey_revolutionary_war_sites/towns/sandy_hook_nj_revolutionary_war_sites.htm |publisher=Revolutionary War New Jersey}}</ref>
