{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}} {{Use Australian English|date=January 2016}} {{Infobox Officeholder | honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]] | name = Jane Aagaard | honorific-suffix = | small | caption = |birth_name = Jane Lesley Aagaard | order = 8th | office = Speaker of the Northern Territory Legislative Assembly | term_start = 29 June 2005 | term_end = 23 October 2012 | deputy = | predecessor = [[Loraine Braham]] | successor = [[Kezia Purick]] | constituency_AM2 = [[Electoral division of Nightcliff|Nightcliff]] | assembly2 = Northern Territory Legislative | term_start2 = 18 August 2001 | term_end2 = 6 August 2012 | predecessor2 = [[Stephen Hatton]] | successor2 = [[Natasha Fyles]] | birth_date = {{birth year and age|1956}} | birth_place = [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = [[Australia]]n | party = [[Australian Labor Party (Northern Territory Branch)|Labor Party]] | spouse = | relations = | children = Zoe, Michael, Alex | residence = | alma_mater = [[Queensland University of Technology|QUT]] | occupation = Public relations officer | profession = | religion = Uniting Church | signature = | website = | footnotes = }}
'''Jane Lesley Aagaard''' (born 1956) is a former [[Australia]]n politician. She was an [[Australian Labor Party (Northern Territory Branch)|Labor Party]] member of the [[Northern Territory Legislative Assembly]] from 2001 to 2012, representing the [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]]-based electorate of [[electoral division of Nightcliff|Nightcliff]]. She was the [[Speaker of the Northern Territory Legislative Assembly|Speaker of the Assembly]] from June 2005 until October 2012—to date, the only Labor member ever to hold the post. Prior to holding the speakership, she had served as Health Minister from 2001 to 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.curriculum.edu.au/parl.php3?srch=parl&list_params=gender%3D%26offices_held%3D%26party%3D%26parliament%3D%26surname%3DAagaard%26electorate%3D%26former_occupations%3D&ID=612|title=Hon. Jane Lesley AAGAARD MLA|publisher=Australian Government|accessdate=2009-09-22}}</ref>
== Early life == Jane Aagaard was born in [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] in 1956, to John Stuart McIntosh and Jean Brown. She moved to [[Brisbane]], [[Queensland]] at the age of seven, where she was educated at [[Somerville House]], a school for girls in [[South Brisbane]].<ref name=Whoswho>{{cite encyclopedia| editor = Suzannah Pearce| encyclopedia = Who's Who in Business Live!| title = AAGAARD Jane Lesley, Hon. |date=2006-11-17| publisher = Crown Content Pty Ltd| location = North Melbourne, Vic}}</ref>
In 1986, she accepted a position with the Northern Territory Department of Mines and Energy, and settled with her husband in Darwin.
Aagaard also became heavily involved in many aspects of the Darwin community. She helped found the [[Brolga Awards]] and [[Northern Territory Sports Awards]], and continued organising both presentations for several years. Not long before entering parliament, she had also organised the city's commemoration of its bombing by [[Japan]]ese forces during [[World War II]].<ref>Smith, Camden. "Aagaard to stand for Nightcliff seat". ''[[Northern Territory News]]'', 7 March 2001.</ref>
When former [[Chief Minister of the Northern Territory|Chief Minister]] [[Stephen Hatton]], the longtime [[Country Liberal Party|CLP]] member for Nightcliff, retired at the 2001 election, Aagaard ran as the Labor candidate against Hatton's son, Jason. In a shock result, Aagaard won the seat on an unexpectedly large swing of 11.7 percent that saw the previously marginal Nightcliff technically become a safe Labor seat. Aagaard's victory was part of a six-seat swing to Labor that saw the party win government for the first time ever, mainly on the strength of a strong performance in the Darwin area. She was reelected in 2005, picking up a healthy swing of 8.5 percent
In March 2012, Aargard announced that she would not contest [[Northern Territory general election, 2012|the next election]] due to "ongoing medical issues that would require treatment and surgery".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntnews.com.au/article/2012/03/25/295785_ntnews.html |title=Speaker Aagaard to retire from politics |publisher=NT News |date=25 March 2012 |accessdate=16 April 2012}}</ref> In November 2012, Aargard was granted the title The Honourable for life.<ref name=gazette>[http://www.comlaw.gov.au/Details/C2012G00283 Ms Jane Lesley Aagaard granted the title "Honourable" for life], ''Commonwealth Government Gazette'' C2012G00283, S No. 177 of 2012, 20 November 2012.</ref>
