{{Infobox military conflict | conflict = Intertribal battle | width = | partof = | image = | caption = | date = Likely 1830 | place = Mid-central present-day Nebraska | coordinates = | map_type = | map_relief = | latitude = | longitude = | map_size = | map_marksize = | map_caption = | map_label = | territory = | result = Pawnee victory | status = | combatants_header = | combatant1 = Cheyenne, Arapaho and Lakota | combatant2 = Skidi Pawnee and some Pawnee from the South Bands | commander1 = Unknown | commander2 = Chief Big Eagle, keeper of the Morning Star bundle | units1 = | units2 = | strength1 = The whole Cheyenne tribe and an unknown number of allies | strength2 = Unknown, but a big Pawnee camp | casualties1 = Unknown | casualties2 = Unknown | notes = The Cheyenne lost the Sacred Arrows during the battle, described as "the greatest disaster" in Cheyenne history. | campaignbox = }}
'''''The Pawnee capture of the Cheyenne Sacred Arrows''''' occurred around 1830 in central [[Nebraska]], when the [[Cheyenne]] attacked a group from the [[Skidi|Skidi Pawnee]] tribe, who were hunting [[bison]]. The Cheyenne had with them their [[sacred bundle]] of four [[arrow]]s, called the Mahuts. During the battle, this sacred, ceremonial object was taken by the Pawnee. The Cheyenne initially made replica arrows but also tried to get the originals back. They recovered one from the Pawnee directly, either given to them or taken by them, and a second was captured by the [[Lakota people|Lakota]] and returned to the Cheyenne in exchange for horses. The two corresponding replicas were ceremonially returned to the [[Black Hills]], where the arrows were traditionally believed to have originated. Eventually the bundles were re-established and the societies and their ceremonies continue into the present day.
==Background== Likely, the [[Pawnee people|Pawnee]] lived in villages of earth lodges in the present-day state of [[Nebraska]]<ref name=Blaine1990>Blaine, Martha R. (1990): ''Pawnee Passage, 1870-1875''. Norman and London.</ref>{{rp|32}} and northern [[Kansas]]<ref name=Murie1981>{{cite journal |last1=Murie |first1=James R. |last2=Parks |first2=Douglas R. |title=Ceremonies of the Pawnee, Part II: The South Bands |journal=[[Smithsonian Contributions to Anthropology]] |date=1981 |volume=27 |issue=2 |url=https://repository.si.edu/handle/10088/1338 |accessdate=19 July 2018 |oclc=7963188}}</ref>{{rp|5}} already in the 16th century.<ref name=Wedel1982>Wedel, Mildred Mott (1982): "The Wichita Indian in the Arkansas River Basin". ''Smithsonian Contributions to Anthropology''. No. 30, pp. 118-134. Washington.</ref>{{rp|121}} At the time of the battle with the [[Cheyenne]], the [[Skidi]] Pawnee populated the banks of [[Loup River]] in the central part of Nebraska. The Chawi, the Kitkahahki and the Pitahawirata made up the South Bands<ref name=Murie1981/>{{rp|183, 195 and 199}} as they lived south of the [[Platte River]].<ref name=Murie1981/>{{rp|4}} <ref name=Blaine1990/>{{rp|72}} Just some years later, they would move north and gather in the same area as the Skidi Pawnee.<ref name=Jensen1994>{{cite journal |last1=Jensen |first1=Richard E |title=The Pawnee Mission, 1834-1846 |journal=[[Nebraska History]] |date=1994 |volume=75 |pages=301-310 |url=https://history.nebraska.gov/sites/history.nebraska.gov/files/doc/publications/NH1994PawneeMission.pdf |accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref>{{rp|305}} The Pawnee raised corn and other crops near their villages. However, they went on long communal [[bison]] hunts in both summer and winter. While out on the [[Great Plains|plains]], they lived in skin tents and [[tipi]]s.<ref name=Blaine1990/>{{rp|71-84}}
The final groups of Cheyenne Indians seem to have crossed the [[Missouri River]] from eastern [[North Dakota]] in the last quarter of the 18th century. For a while, they lived south of the [[Cannonball River]] near already-established Cheyenne villages or camps.<ref name=Wood2010>{{cite journal |last1=Wood |first1=W. Raymond |title=The Earliest Map of the Mandan Heartland: Notes on the Jarvis and Mackay 1791 Map |journal=Plains Anthropologist |date=2010 |volume=55 |issue=216 |pages=255-276 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/23057064?seq=1#page_scan_tab_contents |accessdate=19 July 2018 |oclc=720372761||url-access=subscription}}</ref>{{rp|272}} In the first decade of the 19th century, they mainly camped north of the [[North Platte River|North Platte]].<ref name=Hyde1987>{{cite book|last1=Bent|first1=George|last2=Hyde|first2=George E.|title=Life of George Bent Written from His Letters|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3gMMEl36-g0C|year=2010|publisher=[[University of Oklahoma Press]]|isbn=978-0-8061-1577-1|author-link1=George Bent|author-link2=George E. Hyde|orig-year=Originally published 1968}}</ref>{{rp|32}} Around 1825, some bands headed south<ref name=Hyde1987/>{{rp|37}} lured by reports about large herds of wild horses between the Platte River and the [[Arkansas River]].<ref name=Hyde1987/>{{rp|33}} This brought them close to the hunting grounds used by the Pawnee.<ref name=Hyde1987/>{{rp|48}}<ref name=Blaine1990/>{{rp|204}}
The Pawnee and the Cheyenne had long been enemies, and had fought each other since the Cheyenne first moved into the area.<ref name=Hyde1987/>{{rp|47}}<ref name="Powell1998">{{cite book|last=Powell|first=Peter J.|title=Sweet Medicine: The Continuing Role of the Sacred Arrows, the Sun Dance, and the Sacred Buffalo Hat in Northern Cheyenne History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vulaSLNuWFQC|year=1998|publisher=[[University of Oklahoma Press]]|isbn=978-0-8061-3028-6}}</ref>{{rp|31}} They captured horses<ref name=Hyde1987/>{{rp|101}} and confronted each other on the plains, but neither side achieved any definite lasting advantage over the other.<ref name=Dorsey1906>{{cite journal |last1=Dorsey |first1=George A. |authorlink1=George Amos Dorsey |title=Pawnee War Tales |journal=American Anthropologist |date=6 April 1906 |volume=8 |issue=2 |pages=337–345 |doi=10.1525/aa.1906.8.2.02a00120 |url=https://anthrosource.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1525/aa.1906.8.2.02a00120 |accessdate=19 July 2018 |oclc=950934936}}</ref><ref name=SIT1972>{{cite book|last1=Timber|first1=John Stands In|last2=Liberty|first2=Margot|last3=Utley|first3=Robert Marshall|title=Cheyenne Memories|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=17EDFc7BhX0C|year=1998|publisher=[[Yale University Press]]|isbn=978-0-300-07300-3}}</ref>{{rp|61-63}}<ref name="Powell1998"/>{{rp|31-2}}
===Sacred Arrows=== [[File:Bear Butte.jpg|thumb|upright 1.2|Bear Butte. The Cheyenne prophet Sweet Medicine received the Sacred Arrows on Bear Butte, South Dakota.]] According to his traditional biography, the Cheyenne ancestral hero [[Sweet Medicine (Cheyenne)|Sweet Medicine]] received the Sacred Arrows as a gift from supernatural beings, after being taken into a sacred cave at [[Bear Butte]] in the [[Black Hills]].<ref name=SIT1972/>{{rp|36}}<ref name="Schaefer2008">{{cite book|last=Schaefer|first=Richard T.|title=Encyclopedia of Race, Ethnicity, and Society|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YMUola6pDnkC|date=20 March 2008|publisher=SAGE|isbn=978-1-4129-2694-2}}</ref>{{rp|268}}<ref name="Waldman2014">{{cite book|last=Waldman|first=Carl|title=Encyclopedia of Native American Tribes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WxomdGVLjZ0C|date=14 May 2014|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-1-4381-1010-3|page=57}}</ref> The two Buffalo Arrows in the bundle were painted red and provided for good hunting.<ref name="Schaefer2008"/>{{rp|268}}<ref name=Grinnell1910>{{cite journal |last1=Grinnell |first1=George Bird |authorlink1=George Bird Grinnell |title=The Great Mysteries of the Cheyenne |journal=[[American Anthropologist]] |date=1910 |volume=12 |issue=4 |pages=542-575 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/659797?seq=1#page_scan_tab_contents |accessdate=19 July 2018 |oclc=40266648}}</ref>{{rp|543}} The two Man Arrows were painted black painted and were instead for war′.<ref name=Grinnell1910/>{{rp|543}} When the four arrows were tied near the top of a [[lance]] in two separate pairs<ref name=Grinnell1910/>{{rp|557}} and carried against an enemy after the performance of the proper ceremony, they promised victory,<ref name=Hyde1987/>{{rp|50}} and had already been present in the total [[Tongue River Massacre (1820)|destruction of a big Crow camp]] at [[Tongue River (Montana)|Tongue River]] in 1820.<ref name=Hyde1987/>{{rp|24-26}}
The renewal of the arrows form one of the most [[sacred]] of the Cheyenne ceremonies, and traditionally take place during the same time every summer, as well as in response to unfortunate events, such as a homicide or other tragedy.<ref name="Schaefer2008"/>{{rp|268}}
==Prelude== A year before this historic battle, a party of Cheyenne warriors intended to raid the Pawnee near the lower Platte. The party was discovered and all killed, just as the Cheyenne had done ten years before after the killing of thirty Cheyenne [[Cheyenne military societies#Bowstring|Bowstring]] warriors by the Crow. The tribe vowed to avenge the war group by moving the against those to blame for the killings.<ref name=Hyde1987/>{{rp|49}}
In the summer of 1830, the entire Cheyenne tribe started down the Platte.{{efn|The year 1830 was agreed upon by a Cheyenne and a Pawnee, both participating in the battle.<ref name=Grinnell1910/>{{rp|556}} Although some give the year as 1833.<ref name=Hyde1987/>{{rp|48}}}} A number of allied [[Lakota people|Lakota]] and [[Arapaho]] joined. The special custodian or keeper of the Sacred Arrows, White Thunder, and his wife led them.<ref name=Hyde1987/>{{rp|49}} The scouts sent out to locate the enemy found no traces of the Pawnee. By chance, the group came across four messengers from a party of scouts, who had been killed by the Pawnee.<ref name=Grinnell1910/>{{rp|557}} The scouts finally located a large camp of Pawnees at the head of the [[Loup River|South Loup]].<ref name=Hyde1987/>{{rp|49}} (According to the Pawnee, they had camp somewhere on Platte River).<ref name=Dorsey1903>{{cite journal |last1=Dorsey |first1=George A. |authorlink1=George Amos Dorsey |title=How the Pawnee Captured the Cheyenne Medicine Arrows |journal=[[American Anthropologist]] |date=1903 |volume=5 |issue=4 |pages=644-658 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/658944 |accessdate=19 July 2018 |oclc=254963378}}</ref>{{rp|644}}
After marching for another day and night march, the body of people reached a place near the Pawnee camp in the early morning. The warriors prepared for battle. The women and children grouped in a circle where they had a view of the flat area soon to become a battlefield.<ref name=Hyde1987/>{{rp|49}} <ref name=Grinnell1910/>{{rp|558}} The Pawnee camp seems to have been hidden on the other side of a ridge.
The Cheyenne warriors and their allies placed themselves in two separate wings. The Sacred Arrows were in front of one wing, and the other wing would follow a man wearing the sacred Buffalo Hat. "These two great medicines protected all who were behind them ... and rendered the enemy in front helpless".<ref name=Hyde1987/>{{rp|50}}
Meanwhile, the first bison hunters left the Pawnee camp and almost stumbled on the lined of the army. The battle was on, and White Thunder was unable to restrain the Cheyenne. Without having performed the required ceremony, he handed over the arrow bundle to a selected medicine man named Bull. Bull in turn hastily tied the whole bundle to the middle of his lance.<ref name=Dorsey1903/>{{rp|646}} Then he mounted his horse and tried to catch up with the rest of the warriors.<ref name=Hyde1987/>{{rp|57}}
==Battle== [[File:The area where the Pawnee captured the Sacred Arrows of the Cheyenne.jpg|thumb|upright 2.7|The area where the Pawnee captured the Sacred Arrows of the Cheyenne]] "The battle was hard fought".<ref name=Dorsey1903/>{{rp|647}} An old Pawnee, apparently a Pitahawirata<ref name=Grinnell1910/>{{rp|552}} from the South Bands, was sick and tired of living. He had told his relatives to carry him to the very [[front line]] of the battle.<ref name=Dorsey1903/>{{rp|645}} He was sitting on the ground with a bow and some arrows. Bull wanted to [[Counting coup|count coup]] on this enemy, although the rest of the Cheyenne tried to talk him from it.<ref name=Grinnell1910/>{{rp|558}} The old Pawnee avoided the thrust with the lance and seized it. He dragged it from Bull, who slowly rode back to his own line. "This spear must be a wonderful spear ...", shouted the Pawnee, when he saw the medicine bundle in a wrapping of hide tied to it. The Pawnee rushed forward. Chief Big Eagle came first and secured the lance before the Cheyenne could recapture it.<ref name=Dorsey1903/>{{rp|649}}<ref name="Powell1998"/>{{rp|37}}
During the fight, Chief Big Eagle wore the Wonderful Leggings of Pahukatawa. The leggings were a part of a tribal war bundle, and they seemed to make Big Eagle fearless. "Through the power of these leggings the Skiri [Skidi] captured the wonderful Cheyenne arrows".<ref name=MuriepartI>{{cite journal |last1=Murie |first1=James R. |last2=Parks |first2=Douglas R. |title=Ceremonies of the Pawnee, Part I: The Skiri |journal=[[Smithsonian Contributions to Anthropology]] |date=1981 |volume=27 |url=https://repository.si.edu/handle/10088/1337 |accessdate=19 July 2018 |oclc=756235349}}</ref>{{rp|66}} Further, Big Eagle was dressed in a red shirt and wore a government medal on his breast. Throughout the battle, he rode on a small spotted horse. Therefore, the Cheyenne remembered him as Spotted Horse or Big Spotted Horse.<ref name=Dorsey1903/>{{rp|648}} <ref name=Grinnell1910/>{{rp|552}}
According to the Cheyenne, they killed the old Pawnee on the battlefield.<ref name=Grinnell1910/>{{rp|558}} The Pawnee say, he first died the next summer during a Cheyenne attack on an almost empty Pawnee village.<ref name=Dorsey1903/>{{rp|651}}
With the Sacred Arrows gone and [[morale]] low, the Cheyenne failed to withstand a renewed charge by the Pawnee and retreated.<ref name="Powell1998"/>{{rp|37-8}} "How many were killed on either side was not known".<ref name=Grinnell1910/>{{rp|558}} Later, the Cheyenne retreated up the Platte, mourning the loss of the arrows, which [[George Bent]] described as "... the greatest disaster the Cheyennes ever suffered."<ref name=Hyde1987/>{{rp|51}}<ref name=Hyde1987/>{{rp|152}}
==Aftermath== Pawnee Chief Big Eagle concluded they had captured something of extraordinary importance when he examined the arrows. He was keeper of the [[Pawnee mythology|Morning Star]] bundle of the Skidi Pawnee and placed three of the arrows in that bundle.<ref name=Dorsey1903/>{{rp|650}} <ref name=MuriepartI/>{{rp|66}}
Some time after the battle, the best Cheyenne arrow makers made four surrogate Sacred Arrows.<ref name=Hyde1987/>{{rp|53}}<ref name=Grinnell1910/>{{rp|558-560}} However, they also tried in various ways to retrieve the originals. Once, they invited Big Eagle and the Pawnees to their camp. In return for the four arrows they promised the guests many horses. Big Eagle expected treachery and brought just one arrow wrapped in a bundle. As feared, a Cheyenne rode away with the arrow in an unguarded moment.<ref name=Dorsey1903/>{{rp|657}} Another source recounts that three Cheyenne, White Thunder, Old Bark, and Doll Man traveled to a Skidi village in 1835 where they were received in Big Eagle's lodge and given one Buffalo Arrow. Despite gifts of more than a hundred horses, no more arrows were returned.<ref name="Powell1998"/>{{rp|39}}
[[File:Lakota winter counts showing the Sacred Arrow of the Cheyennes returned in 1843.jpg|thumb|upright 0.9|Pictures from two Lakota winter counts, 1843-1844. A Sacred Arrow of the Cheyenne was returned by the Lakota.]] In either the winter of 1843 to 1844 according to a contemporary source,<ref name=Mallory1886>{{cite book|title=Annual Report of the Bureau of American Ethnology to the Secretary of the Smithsonian Institution|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jslZ_qeu5zAC|year=1886|publisher=[[U.S. Government Printing Office]]|chapter=The Corbusier Winter Counts|oclc=651911152}}</ref>{{rp|141}}, or in 1837 according to more modern sources,<ref name="Powell1998"/>{{rp|39}}<ref name="Lookingbill2015">{{cite book|last=Lookingbill|first=Brad D.|title=A Companion to Custer and the Little Bighorn Campaign|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gV6aCgAAQBAJ|date=10 September 2015|publisher=Wiley|isbn=978-1-119-07188-4}}</ref> the Lakota attacked a village of Pawnee and retrieved a single medicine arrow. They recognized the Man Arrow and returned it to the Cheyenne in exchange for one hundred horses.<ref name="Powell1998"/>{{rp|39}}<ref name=Mallory1886/>{{rp|141}}
Two of the remade Sacred Arrows were now in excess. A ceremony was held, and the Cheyenne left two of the new arrows in a bundle in a crevice of the Black Hills, near the place where Sweet Medicine had received the original arrows. There they remained for a long while, and were occasional visited by Cheyenne travelers, before eventually disappearing.<ref name=Hyde1987/>{{rp|55}}<ref name="Grinnell2008">{{cite book|last=Grinnell|first=George Bird|title=The Cheyenne Indians: Their History and Lifeways : Edited and Illustrated|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GzxHTeOe8FcC|year=2008|publisher=[[World Wisdom]]|isbn=978-1-933316-60-4}}</ref>{{rp|224}}
Efforts to restore the additional two original arrows were again made in the 1890s and 1930s to no avail.<ref name="Powell1998"/>{{rp|40-1}} The return of the remaining arrows remained a source of bitterness for generations.<ref name="Lookingbill2015"/>
